From: LLVM Developer <dev@llvm.org>
Date: Tue, 22 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/3] [DAGCombiner] Merge consecutive stores of the same value
 into a vector splat store

When multiple consecutive stores write the same value to adjacent memory
locations, merge them into a single wider vector store using a splat
pattern. This is a common idiom in linked-list manipulation code (e.g.,
poisoning a detached node's pointers with self-references) and in struct
initialization.

Previously, the store merging pass only handled Constants, Loads, and
Extract sources. This patch adds a SplatValue source type that detects
runs of stores writing the same SSA value to consecutive addresses and
replaces them with BUILD_VECTOR + a single wide store.

For the doubly-linked-list detach pattern:

  n->next = n->prev = n;  // two 8-byte stores of the same pointer

Before: two separate 8-byte stores (movq + movq)
After:  one 16-byte vector store (pshufd + movdqu on SSE, stp on AArch64)

This is target-independent: the DAGCombiner will only merge when the
target's legal types support the wider store width.

---
